The Gauteng provincial government was committed to helping victims of gender-based violence through the Ikhaya leThemba initiative programmes, MEC for community safety and transport Sizakele Nkosi-Malobane said on Wednesday.She was delivering her budget vote speech, and made allusions in her speech that her department was committed to ending violence against women and children.&#8220;In the ready to govern document of the ANC we declared that women should be able to walk the streets freely without fear of assault and to feel safe and free from violence in their own homes,&#8221; she said.She said there was a need for young men to display the courage of the 1976 generation, emulating the likes of Tsietsi Mashinini, among others, to defend the rights of women.Nkosi-Malobane said police visibility was the focal point of her department, and this initiative would help to improve crime prevention.&#8220;Criminals must be squeezed out of Gauteng. It is time we claim our streets back and allow the Gauteng citizens to walk the streets without fear,&#8221; Nkosi-Malobane said.#ANCGPAtWork Comrade Nkosi-Malobane: We pleased that the @SAPoliceService has reintroduced specialist units: murder, narcotics, corruption Gauteng ANC (@GautengANC) June 28, 2017#ANCGPAtWork Comrade @NkosiMalobane also spoke about station visits, safety kiosks and quarterly review sessions as part of dept priorities. pic.twitter.com/Kk2YV6ChPL Gauteng ANC (@GautengANC) June 28, 2017MEC Nkosi-Malobane also mentioned that the Community Police Forum (CPF) structures&#8217; functionality will be with Provincial and Cluster Boards.#ANCGPAtWork ANC-led @GP_CommSafety remains committed to helping victims of gender based violence, through initiatives like Ikhaya leThemba pic.twitter.com/sz2wZqBhEB Gauteng ANC (@GautengANC) June 28, 2017#ANCGPAtWork The @GP_CommSafety is also aiming to reduce accidents and road fatalities, along with curbing taxi violence in Gauteng. pic.twitter.com/Y7a5qdvJQ2 Gauteng ANC (@GautengANC) June 28, 2017-TNA Reporter 